  "original_title": "Sri Lanka telephone, data tariffs up by 20-pct",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka telephone, data tariffs up by 20-pct",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 All three mobile service providers in Sri Lanka increased call and data tariffs by 20 percent following the 15 percent value added tax (VAT) with effect from September 05, data providers said.",
        "SLTC Mobitel, the local mobile service provider and Dialog Axiata announced it will increase the Mobile Broadband Plans and value added services by 20 percent and Pay TV by 25 percent.",
        "\u201cWe the licensed telecommunication service providers wish to inform due to escalation of operational costs resulting from the devaluation of the rupee, we are compelled to increase tariffs,\u201d both the operators announced on their websites.",
        "\u201cAccordingly, as approved by the Telecommunications Regulatory Commission of Sri Lanka (TRCSL), tariffs on Mobile, Fixed Telephone, Broadband Plans and Value Added Services (Prepaid and Postpaid) will be increased by 20%, while tariffs on all Pay Television Services will be increased by 25%.\u201d",
        "Sri Lanka\u2019s president announced in his interim budget for 2022 that value-added tax (VAT) will be increased to 15 percent from 12 percent starting September 01.",
        "Other telephony and broadband providers too announced they had increased their tariffs.",
        "The Indian mobile service provider Airtel said calll, sms, data and VAS would be increased. (Colombo/Sept04/2022)"
      ],
